Load packages

library(tidyverse) 
library(datasauRus)

Exercise 1

(1,846 rows with 12 columns and 3 variables, Variables include dataset, x, and y values)

Exercise 2

dino_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "dino")

ggplot(data = dino_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

And next calculate the correlation between x and y in this dataset:

dino_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0645

Exercise 3

Plotting a star

star_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "star")

ggplot(data = star_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

Finding the correlation coefficient

star_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0630

Compared with the value of r from exercise 2, the value is extremely close in relation to one another.


### Exercise 4

Plotting a circle
circle_data <- datasaurus_dozen %>%
  filter(dataset == "circle")

ggplot(data = circle_data, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

R-value for the circle graph
circle_data %>%
  summarize(r = cor(x, y))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##         r
##     <dbl>
## 1 -0.0683
Again, compared with the value of the r value for the dino graph it is extremely close. 

### Exercise 5
Plotting everything
ggplot(data = datasaurus_dozen, aes(x = x, y = y, color = dataset)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~ dataset, ncol = 3) +
  theme(legend.position = "none")
